<para>
On Linux systems (Mandrake 9 and Red Hat 8 and 9), &sr; binaries can
be <link linkend="sec.rpminst">installed via an <acronym>RPM</acronym>
package</link> or <link linkend="sec.source_inst">from &sr;'s source
code distribution</link>.  The &sr; <acronym>RPM</acronym>
distribution does <emphasis>not</emphasis> provide support for
<acronym>PETSc</acronym> or <acronym>ITK</acronym>.
<acronym>PETSc</acronym> and <acronym>ITK</acronym> support is
available only through the &sr; source code distribution.
</para>

<para>
On SGI and &osx; systems &sr; must be <link
linkend="sec.source_inst">installed from the source code
distribution</link>.
</para>

<para>
Read  <citetitle pubwork="section"><xref
endterm="title.prepare" linkend="sec.prepare"/></citetitle> after
installing &sr;.
</para>

<para>
Start with <citetitle
pubwork="section"><xref linkend="sec.rpminst"
endterm="title.rpminst"/></citetitle> if installing &sr; from an
<acronym>RPM</acronym>.  Otherwise, proceed as follows:
<orderedlist>
<listitem>
<para>Read <citetitle pubwork="section"><xref linkend="sec.opt_inst"
endterm="title.opt_inst"/></citetitle> if installing
<acronym>PETSc</acronym> or Insight Toolkit (<acronym>ITK</acronym>)
support.  Note that support for <acronym>PETSc</acronym> and
<acronym>ITK</acronym> is not provided by Linux <acronym>RPM</acronym>
&sr; distributions.</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>Proceed to <citetitle
pubwork="section"><xref linkend="sec.source_inst"
endterm="title.source_inst"/></citetitle> to install &sr; from 
source code.</para>
</listitem>
</orderedlist>
</para>

<section id="intro.nvidia_notes">
<title id="intro.nvidia_notes.title">Linux and Nvidia Driver Notes</title>

<para>
Nvidia drivers, versions 1.0-5328 and 1.0-5336, will not work for
hardware based texture volume rendering in SCIRun.  Please do not
update to these drivers if you wish your volume rendering to work.
</para>

<para>Driver versions 1.0-4496, 1.0-4363 are known to work.</para>

<para>
Driver version 1.0-4191 does not work.  SCI has not tested versions
earlier than 1.0-4191&mdash;they may or may not work.
</para>

</section>

<section id="intro.ati_notes">
<title id="intro.ati_notes.title">Linux and ATI Graphics Cards Notes</title>

<para>The SCI Institute has spent some time experimenting with the use
of ATI graphics cards under the Linux operating system.  Several
different ATI cards and several different flavors of Linux have been
tried with mixed results:
<itemizedlist>
<listitem>
<para>On one system, ATI drivers installed with apparent success, but
the system did not report using the drivers and only software
rendering appeared to be used.</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>Under Red Hat Enterprise the drivers installed and worked, but the
graphics were very choppy, producing a mostly unusable rendering.</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>On another system, drivers installed and were used but vertex
arrays did not work, which caused some objects to be rendered
incorrectly</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>One card did work well under Redhat 9.</para>
</listitem>
</itemizedlist>
Based on these experiences, SCI does not recommend the use of ATI
cards with &sr; software at this time.  We suggest the use of an
NVidia card instead.  SCI investigate ATI cards further when
ATI releases new drivers.
</para>
</section>

<section id="intro.redhat_ent_notes">
<title id="intro.redhat_ent_notes.title">Redhat Enterprise
Notes</title> 

<para>SCI has experienced a number of strange behaviors when running
&sr; on Red Hat Enterprise Linux.  We do not recommend running &sr; on
this system at this time.  SCI will evaluate future versions of Redhat
Enterprise</para>
</section>

</section>

